Architecture Notes — load-bearing, do not touch without reading

Coordinate Pipeline
  screenToDocument / documentToScreen / quadVertexShaderWithTransform
  must stay in sync at all times. Any change to one requires retest of
  all three on physical iPad. Source of Phase 1's major bugs; must not
  regress.

  Canvas texture: 4096×4096 (sized from view.drawableSize, not
    view.bounds.size).
  fitSize model: max(viewport.w, viewport.h) — fill, not fit.
  Rotation convention: shader Y-up (visual CCW), Swift R(-θ) for
    Y-down equivalent.
  Marquee selection: stored as 4-point screen-space polygon mapped to
    doc space via screenToDocument. Routes through lasso pipeline.
    activeSelection is nil for all marquee selections — selectionPath
    is ground truth.

Pressure → Render Pipeline
  Apple Pencil firmware can return NaN force samples; the pressure
  path is NaN-guarded at four points (computePressure, touchesMoved
  interpolation, renderStroke per-point, shader clamp). Apple GPU
  point sprites cap at ~511 px; the brush vertex shader clamps
  out.pointSize to [0, 511] as the universal guarantee. Don't remove
  these guards without redoing the analysis in the Investigations
  Reference below.

Composite Sampling
  CanvasRenderer.compositeLayersToTexture(layers:) renders all visible
  layers over an opaque white background and returns the resulting
  MTL texture. Output has alpha = 1.0 and straight RGB equal to what's
  on screen. Used by Export to Photos (via compositeLayersToImage)
  and the eyedropper. One full 4096×4096 pass per call; only fired on
  user action, not per frame.

Memory
  4096×4096 × 4 bytes = 64 MB per layer.
  5 layers = 320 MB — monitor on base iPad, fine on iPad Pro.
  HistoryManager caps at 50 snapshots; each snapshot is 64 MB; the
  effective limit is the memory ceiling, not the count.

Worker Auth
  No auth, no rate limiting, CORS wide open as of today — must be
  closed BEFORE TestFlight goes wide, not after. Plan and phased
  checklist live in /authandratelimitingandsecurity.md (Phase 5
  covers Worker hardening: JWT gate, drawing_id ownership check,
  tier-aware quotas via TIER_LIMITS, per-IP backstop, abuse
  webhook). Worker code is already structured for it — getUserTier
  and fetchCritiqueHistory are stubs ready to be wired.
  API key lives in Cloudflare Worker env var OPENAI_API_KEY.
  Deploy via `wrangler deploy` from cloudflare-worker/ with
  CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN set.


Investigations Reference

Worker prompt construction externalized + tier-aware (Apr 28, test-
suite-verified, no iPad retest needed):
  Root cause to solve later, addressed now: every prompt iteration
  used to require touching the request handler in cloudflare-worker/
  index.js — system prompt, skill calibration block, response format
  template, and OpenAI call were all interleaved as one ~50-line
  template literal. Made it hard to A/B prompt variants, hard to
  introduce per-tier behavior cleanly (planned in
  authandratelimitingandsecurity.md), and hard to pull the past-
  critique-context feature into the prompt without a rewrite.

  Done in a single pass to avoid double-touching index.js when
  Phase 5 of the auth plan lands:
    • PromptConfig shape documented at top of file. Fields:
      systemPrompt, includeHistoryCount, historyFraming,
      styleModifier, maxOutputTokens.
    • Two presets exported: DEFAULT_FREE_CONFIG (history 2, tokens
      1000) and DEFAULT_PRO_CONFIG (history 5, tokens 1500). Pro
      preset's styleModifier is null in the constant; selectConfig
      merges in app_metadata.prompt_preferences.styleModifier at
      request time so per-Pro-user customization doesn't pollute the
      preset (a returned-config-mutation guard is covered by a unit
      test).
    • Pure helpers extracted: selectConfig(tier, prefs),
      buildSystemPrompt(config, context), buildUserMessage(config,
      history, image), formatHistoryEntries(entries),
      renderSkillCalibration(skillLevel), renderContextBlock(context).
      Pure functions = trivially testable in Node without spinning
      up workerd.
    • Two stubs added for the not-yet-wired pieces:
      getUserTier(jwt, env) returns { tier: 'free',
      promptPreferences: null } until Phase 5a wires JWT validation;
      fetchCritiqueHistory(drawingId, env) returns [] until Phase 2
      ships the drawings table. Existing clients see no behavior
      change today; new clients can start sending drawingId
      forward-compatibly.
    • test.mjs + package.json with "type": "module" added.
      `node --test test.mjs` runs in <0.3s. Six tests cover: free
      with no history → no history block; free preset ignores
      styleModifier even if prompt_preferences provided; pro with 3
      critiques + modifier injects all three and appends modifier;
      pro caps history at includeHistoryCount when more is supplied;
      tier override (free vs pro vs unknown-tier-fallback-to-free);
      mutation isolation between selectConfig calls.
    • Existing prompt content preserved verbatim — BASE_SYSTEM_PROMPT,
      RESPONSE_FORMAT_TEMPLATE, skill-level calibration text are the
      same strings as before the refactor. Only structure changed.

  Why it landed before auth/quotas: pure prep work. Once Phase 5
  starts, the only Worker-side additions left are JWT validation +
  Postgres reads + KV-backed quota counters. The prompt scaffolding
  is out of the way.

  No client contract change. iOS app sends the same payload
  ({ image, context }); drawingId is optional and ignored by the
  history stub. Authorization header is read but not validated yet.

Pencil "stroke vanishes mid-stroke under heavy pressure" — two causes
(both addressed Apr 16):
  (1) NaN propagation. Swift's max(0, NaN) returns NaN, not 0. A
      single NaN force sample taints the stroke via interpolation
      (previousPressure ?? samplePressure) → all subsequent stamps
      have NaN pressure → Metal silently skips them.
  (2) Metal point sprite cap (~511 px on Apple A-series; M-series may
      be higher). renderStrokePreview multiplies by textureToScreen
      (~1.33) and zoomScale, so brush 200 + zoom 2 = 532, past the
      cap → silent fail.
  Both cause "stroke vanishes mid-stroke" depending on which trips
  first. Affects all tools because brush/eraser/line/rect/circle all
  route through the same pressure → point sprite path.

"Large brush size breaks the whole thing" — three causes (Apr 16):
  (1) BIG ONE: lastPoint updated every coalesced sample regardless of
      whether a stamp committed. At brush 200 + spacing 0.1, the
      threshold is 20 doc px, but Pencil samples land ~2 doc px apart
      → distance never accumulated past 20 → no stamps fired → stroke
      contains exactly one stamp until lift.
  (2) Preview pointSize cap exceedance — see above.
  (3) Fragment shader cost is O(size²); 200 px stamp = 40,000
      fragments per stamp at 240 Hz. Less critical than (1) but can
      contribute to GPU stalls at extremes.

Eyedropper "picked wrong color" — three causes (Apr 27):
  (1) Sampled the active layer's texture only. Color the user saw on
      another layer would come back transparent (or wrong).
  (2) Layer textures store premultiplied RGBA (per the brush fragment
      shader); reading raw bytes into UIColor produced muddy
      half-bright colors at any non-opaque pixel.
  (3) Tap on alpha-0 canvas silently set the brush to transparent
      black; subsequent strokes appeared to vanish.
  Fix: composite visible layers over white, sample that, un-premultiply
  by alpha (no-op on the composite since alpha = 1.0), bail if alpha
  < 0.01.

Color picker "couldn't pick muted colors" — single cause (Apr 27):
  AdvancedColorPicker.updateFromColor and the preset-tap handler both
  pulled hue out of the incoming color and forced saturation,
  brightness, and alpha to 1.0. Tapping black/white/gray gave you red;
  reopening the picker after picking anything muted snapped back.
  Fix: pass all four HSBA components through as-is. Apr 27 follow-up:
  Trevor wanted the SLIDERS to default to full saturation/brightness
  on open (so any hue change starts vivid) while preset taps still pick
  the actual preset color. updateFromColor now keeps the brush's hue +
  alpha but forces sat/bright to 1.0 and writes back; preset taps stay
  unchanged (pick exact preset color).

Brush opacity slider "10% looks like 100% within a single stroke"
(Apr 27, slider REMOVED for v1.0): each stamp blends at slider
opacity O with sourceAlpha/oneMinusSourceAlpha and overlapping stamps
within one stroke accumulate as 1 - (1-O)^n which approaches 1.0
fast. Default spacing 0.1 puts ~10 stamps per brush diameter, so a
10% stroke easily hits ~100% alpha.

Two band-aid attempts on Apr 27 both failed:
  1. Scratch-buffer commit path: stamp into a fresh 4096×4096 scratch
     at opacity = 1.0, then composite scratch onto layer at slider
     opacity. Mathematically correct but softlocked features on iPad
     — likely the +64 MB allocation + two sequential
     waitUntilCompleted() calls per stroke blocking the main thread
     while the GPU stalled. Reverted.
  2. Max-blend pipeline: cloned the brush pipeline with
     alphaBlendOperation = .max so per-pixel alpha caps at the
     highest stamp's contribution. Capped alpha correctly but RGB
     still accumulated through standard sourceAlpha blending, so the
     committed pixel had RGB > alpha (e.g. (1, 0, 0, 0.5) instead of
     premultiplied (0.5, 0, 0, 0.5)). When displayed via the
     premultiplied compositor the RGB > alpha state rendered as over-
     bright color — the visible result was still ~full-color even
     though alpha capped. Reverted.

