Free-transform handles for floating selections (Apr 27, needs iPad
retest, biggest UX surface area added in this pass):

  Goal: rect/lasso/import all share one "floating selection" model
  with corner + edge + rotation handles, like Procreate's free-
  transform. Move tool's whole-layer drag is unaffected (no handles —
  scaling the whole layer isn't a meaningful operation here).

  Pieces:
  • CGFloat → CGSize refactor for selectionScale. Identity is
    CGSize(1, 1). 8 call sites updated; corners use uniform (width
    == height), edges use one-axis (only one component changes).
  • Shader: quadVertexShaderForRect now takes a selectionRotation
    uniform at buffer index 4. Applied IN DOC SPACE around the rect's
    center via R(-θ) for visual CCW (matches canvasRotation
    convention; composes correctly with the canvas-level rotation
    applied later in screen space — visible angle = θ_sel + canvasRot).
  • Renderer: renderFloatingTexture and compositeFloatingTextureIntoLayer
    plumb rotation through.
  • TransformHandlesOverlay (Views/SelectionOverlays.swift): SwiftUI
    overlay rendered in the canvas ZStack. Computes 4 corner + 4 edge
    + 1 rotation handle screen positions every frame:
      1. Build local-frame corners/edges from displayed half-extents.
      2. Apply selectionRotation in doc (R(-θ)) — the SAME rotation
         the shader applies, so handles land on the rendered corners.
      3. Translate by displayed-rect center (in doc space).
      4. documentToScreen() for SwiftUI .position.
    Rotation is applied to handle positions BEFORE the screen
    conversion — never as a post-render .rotationEffect on the
    overlay, which would put handles in the wrong place once
    canvasRotation also kicks in.
  • Handle hit-tests: 16pt visual circles wrapped in 44pt clear
    Rectangle for touch target (Apple HIG minimum).
  • Scale gesture math: project finger displacement onto the original
    diagonal direction (corners — uniform), or onto one axis (edges).
    factor clamped to ≥ 0.05 (no flips in v1.0). Anchor (opposite
    corner / edge midpoint) is pinned in DOC SPACE for the gesture's
    duration; selectionOffset is solved each frame so the new center
    + rotation + scale puts the anchor back at its captured doc
    point. Without this compensation, scaling around origin would
    drift the box away from the anchor.
  • Rotation gesture: angle from rect center to finger via atan2;
    visual CCW = -(currentAngle - initialAngle) (atan2 increases CW
    visually in Y-down screen space).
  • isPointInSelection now rotation-aware: when the floating
    selection is rotated, we inverse-rotate the touch point around
    the displayed rect's center via R(+θ) and check axis-aligned
    containment in local frame. Required so taps inside a rotated
    selection still trigger a body drag.

  Commit / cancel UX:
  • Tap-outside (in MetalCanvasView.touchesBegan, after the drag-
    detection block fails) auto-commits any active floating selection
    or whole-layer move drag, then continues the touch's normal
    behavior (e.g., starting a new brush stroke at the tap point).
    Mirrors Procreate.
  • Tool-change in $currentTool sink. EXCEPTION: switching TO the
    move tool does NOT commit, because move's whole job is to drag
    the floating selection. Without this exception, switching to move
    after a rect/lasso would commit the selection, then drag the
    whole layer — exactly the opposite of intent.
  • Cancel pill (TransformCancelPill, top-center, only visible while
    floatingSelectionTexture is non-nil). cancelSelection() restores
    selectionBeforeSnapshot to the layer and clearSelection()s. No
    history entry recorded — the entire transform session collapses
    to undo-once, per user's "one undo per session" answer.

  Quality preservation on scale (per user's "stash original" rule):
  selectionOriginalSource was already added during (1) for image
  import. scheduleFloatingTextureResampleFromSource() now resamples
  this UIImage to the new displayed pixel size on Task.detached(
  priority: .userInitiated) every time a scale gesture ends. The
  bilinear-scaled GPU texture stays visible until the swap completes
  (off-main-thread per user's explicit instruction). Stale-scale
  guard: the swap is skipped if the user has dragged again before
  the resample finishes — applying a stale-size texture would briefly
  look wrong before the next resample replaces it.

  Out of scope (deferred):
  • Skew (no UI without modifier keys on iPad).
  • Per-handle undo (one-undo-per-session per Q4).
  • Snap-to-aspect-ratio during edge drag.
  • Rotation snapping (15° increments).
  • Negative-scale flip — currently clamped at 0.05 to avoid
    degenerate zero-area rects.
  • Resample cancellation token for back-to-back gestures (current
    stale-scale check tolerates 1-px error and is best-effort; a
    proper sequence number would be cleaner for v1.0.1).

  iPad retest checklist (when Mac/iPad available):
  1. Import an image — appears at 80% of canvas, centered, with
     handles. Bilinear scale during corner-drag; sharp on release.
  2. Corner-drag from each of the 4 corners — uniform scale, opposite
