Image import "too big and stuck" (Apr 27, needs iPad retest):
  Old behavior: importImage aspect-fit at 80% of doc, then immediately
  baked into a fresh layer via the same per-pixel CPU Porter-Duff loop
  that renderImage uses for selection commit. Once baked, the only way
  to reposition was to use the move tool on the whole layer.

  New behavior: import lands as a floating selection on a new (empty)
  layer, sized to 80% of the canvas and centered. The user drags it
  into place using the move tool (or any tap inside the bounds);
  drag-release routes through commitSelection, which blits the
  floating texture into the layer in a single GPU pass. The source
  is CPU-resampled to its displayed pixel size BEFORE the GPU upload
  (no 6000×4000 textures landing on the GPU just to be downsampled by
  the shader), and the original full-res UIImage is stashed on the
  state manager (selectionOriginalSource) so the upcoming scale-
  gesture work resamples from the original each time instead of
  degrading from successive resizes.

  Safety: importing a second image while a prior floating selection
  (rect/lasso extract or earlier import) is uncommitted now commits
  the prior one first instead of silently throwing it away — the
  earlier clearSelection() at the top of importImage was a data-loss
  hazard.

  Related fix: isPointInSelection now falls back to selectionOriginalRect
  when activeSelection / selectionPath are both nil, so tapping inside
  an imported image starts a drag with any tool. (Imports don't draw a
  marquee — the image's own bounds are the visual cue.)

Move/rect/lasso drag was unusably slow (Apr 27, GPU rewrite, needs
iPad retest):
  Root cause: every touchesMoved sample called
  CanvasStateManager.renderSelectionInRealTime, which on each frame
  (1) restored the layer-with-hole snapshot via texture.replace
  (full canvas-sized writeback), then (2) ran the renderImage
  per-pixel premultiplied Porter-Duff loop in CanvasRenderer over the
  selection's bounding box, writing the full canvas back again. For
  the move tool, the "selection" is the entire layer, so every drag
  sample read+wrote the full 4096×4096 texture and ran 16M premul
  blends on the main thread. Pencil samples at ~240 Hz multiply that
  cost — hence "miserably slow."

  Fix: keep the selection as a Metal texture and composite at offset
  on the GPU during drag; never touch CPU pixels until the user lets
  go.
    • New shader quadVertexShaderForRect (Shaders.metal) renders any
      texture covering an arbitrary doc-space rect, applying the same
      zoom/pan/rotation as the layer compositor (and Y-flips offset
      consistent with the existing pan convention so screenToDocument
      stays the inverse of what the user sees).
    • New CanvasRenderer methods: renderFloatingTexture (on-screen
      preview), compositeFloatingTextureIntoLayer (GPU bake on commit
      with the same premultiplied source-over blend as display), and
      translateLayerTextureInPlace (Metal blit triplet for whole-
      layer move commit), plus makeTexture(from: UIImage) to upload
      the extracted selectionPixels once.
    • CanvasStateManager: floatingSelectionTexture is built when
      extractSelectionPixels runs; commitSelection now uses the GPU
      compositor instead of the CPU loop. New
      beginActiveLayerTranslation / commitActiveLayerTranslation pair
      handles move-tool whole-layer drag without extracting at all —
      isTranslatingActiveLayer flags the path so the draw loop
      renders the active layer at offset.
    • MetalCanvasView: touchesMoved during a selection drag now
      ONLY updates selectionOffset (no per-frame compositing). The
      MTKView is in continuous mode at 60 Hz so the next vsync picks
      up the offset and renders. touchesEnded dispatches between
      commitSelection (rect/lasso/move-on-existing-selection) and
      commitActiveLayerTranslation (move-with-no-prior-selection).

  Side benefit: the move tool no longer creates a full-document
  selectionPath/activeSelection on touchesBegan, which is what was
  drawing the unwanted whole-layer marquee. The Hard blockers list
  shrinks from 4 to 3.

  Coordinate-transform note: quadVertexShaderForRect derives its
  doc→screen mapping from the same fitSize=max(viewport.x, viewport.y)
  reasoning as documentToScreen — must stay in sync if the canvas
  sizing ever changes. Y-flip on the offset matches the existing pan
  flip; if a future rework normalises pan to Y-up, this needs to
  follow.

  iPad retest checklist: (a) move tool drag whole layer at zoom 1× /
  3× / 0.5× and at canvas rotations 0° / 45° / 90° — pixels must land
  exactly under the finger on release. (b) Rect select → drag inside
  → release: same. (c) Lasso → drag inside → release: same. (d)
  History: undo restores pre-drag layer. (e) After a rect/lasso
  selection, picking move tool drags only the selection (not the whole
  layer — should NOT call beginActiveLayerTranslation because
  floatingSelectionTexture is non-nil).

Selection marching ants "selection above the ants" — single cause
(Apr 27): the four selection overlays in DrawingCanvasView's ZStack
(previewSelection rect, previewLassoPath, MarchingAntsRectangle,
MarchingAntsPath) were not opting out of safe area, while the MTKView
under them did (.ignoresSafeArea() at line 70). SwiftUI laid the
overlays out inside the safe-area-reduced ZStack frame, so a Path
drawn at "screen y = N" landed at "screen y = N + safeAreaInsets.top"
(~20pt iPad portrait, varies by device/orientation). The pixel
extract/clear/render pipeline used the MTKView's full-screen coord
space (correct), so the actual selected pixels sat above the
visually-displayed marching ants. Side effect: tapping inside the
visible ants to start a drag failed isPointInSelection (touch was
correctly converted to doc space, but landed below the real
selection). Fix: add .ignoresSafeArea() to each of the four overlays.
No coordinate math change. Robust across devices and orientations
because the modifier follows whatever insets the system reports.


